its yet`) that depends on actual subprocess behavior/exit semantics. A fake response would not validate true failure-mode handling. Rejected Integration because behavior text is specifically about repo state observed through real git invocation.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with zero commits, run the CLI, assert exit code is success and stdout is a valid empty report structure (not an error message/traceback).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Correctness is defined against real repository history and must be verified by round-trip observation of externally visible report output. In-process fixtures can validate arithmetic but not full contract with real git history traversal semantics.","test_description":"Construct a repo with known sequence of add/delete/rename/modify commits, run the CLI, and compare emitted counts to expected counts derived from the real commit history scenario.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.11,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real git index vs working-tree mechanics, which are OS/subprocess-backed and easy to misrepresent with mocks. The behavior explicitly compares externally visible CLI output across two real repository states.","test_description":"In a temp repo, create equivalent change sets once as staged and once as unstaged, run CLI for each case, and assert normalized report outputs are identical.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilit